{
  "texts": [
    "Figure 2c shows a scanning image and schematic representation of a photon response memristors.",
    "When exposed to the UV light illumination, tungsten disulfide (indicated by the pink lines in I-V curve) undergoes changes, resulting in the creation of defects such as sulfur vacancies, and hence, the device switches from HRS to LRS.",
    "Conversely, when exposed to oxygen environment, the device switches from LRS to HRS (indicated by the green lines in I-V curve) due to the incorporation of oxygen.Tungsten diselenide (WSe 2) and tungsten disulfide (WS 2) are stable semiconductors with direct bandgap for visible light absorption, positioning them as a promising candidate for photodetector and optoelectronic applications [43,82].",
    "Wang et al.",
    "recently demonstrated the construction of a retinomorphic sensor, where the photoresponses of the sensor are employed to act on a gate terminal within a memristive device, enabling the processing of image data [43]."
  ]
}